50|$|As {{early as}} 1967, Israeli <b>settlement</b> <b>policy</b> {{was started by}} the Labor {{government}} of Levi Eshkol. The basis for Israeli settlement in the West Bank became the Allon Plan, named after its inventor Yigal Allon. It implied Israeli annexation of major parts of the Israeli-occupied territories, especially East Jerusalem, Gush Etzion and the Jordan Valley. The <b>settlement</b> <b>policy</b> {{of the government of}} Yitzhak Rabin, was also derived from the Allon Plan.|$|E
